Great! I halved the sugar and increased the lemon and lime juice. After guests devoured it as a palette cleanser, I used leftovers with white rum to make a daiquiri which was very refreshing and easy to drink, especially when topped up with soda water.

Rating: 4
I have made this using tropical fruits instead of citrus--it's wonderful with passionfruit, mango, or pineapple! It has too much sugar for me, so I put in only 1-1/2 cups for citrus or passionfruit, and 1 cup or even less for sweet fruits like mango or pineapple. Otherwise the recipe as written is a big hit every time I make it.

Rating: 4
This wonderful tasty recipe is a constant hit. Adults and kids love it in summer. I have doubled it due to the demand. If the ginger comes on a little strong, I have re-mixed it in the food processor with lemonade. When I first made it, the ginger taste was very strong so I put it in a martini glass with vodka and it became the biggest hit of the party. Neighbors, my kids and all my neighbors and foodie friends request it constantly.

Rating: 4
I agree with those who say this recipe needs less sugar and more ginger and citrus. I cut the water back to three cups, used a half-cup of sugar, at least 4 tablespoons of chopped ginger, 4 tablespoons of lime and 4 of lemon, 4 teaspoons of each zest. This recipe can more easily be made in an electric ice cream maker after it has cooled. It doesn't need to be frozen twice.

Rating: 4
